<p class="cat hidden-xs hidden-sm"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525/http://www.universetoday.com/category/guide-to-space/" rel="category tag">Guide to Space</a>, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525/http://www.universetoday.com/category/sun/" rel="category tag">sun</a></p>
<h2 class="sing-tit">What Color is the Sun?</h2>
<p class="meta">
<img alt="" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/133873b33f21832bb5c9a376eb278117?s=30&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g" srcset="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/133873b33f21832bb5c9a376eb278117?s=60&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x" class="avatar avatar-30 photo" height="30" width="30"/> <i class="fa fa-clock-o"></i> 8 Oct , 2013 by <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525/http://www.universetoday.com/author/admin/" title="Posts by Fraser Cain" rel="author">Fraser Cain</a>
<i class="fa fa-video-camera"></i> Video
</p>
</div>
   
  
');
}
//--&gt;
</script>
 
<div class="sing-cont">
<div class="sing-spacer">
   
<p>Ask anyone, “what color is the Sun”? and they’ll tell you the obvious answer: it’s yellow. </p>
<p>But is it really? </p>
<p>Please don’t go check, it’s not safe to look directly at the Sun with your unprotected eyes.<br/>
<span id="more-18689"></span><br/>
From our perspective it does look a little yellow, especially after sunrise or shortly before sunset, </p>
<p>But don’t be fooled. </p>
<p>If you could travel into space and look at the Sun without going blind, you’d find that it’s actually white, and not yellow.</p>
<p>Using a prism, you can see how sunlight can be broken up into the spectrum of its colors: red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo and violet. When you mix all those colors together, you get white.</p>
<p>Here’s the strange part. </p>
<p>If look at all the photons coming in, our star is actually sending the most photons in the green portion of the spectrum, </p>
<p>Our Sun appears yellow to us because of the atmosphere.</p>
<p>Photons in the higher end of the spectrum &#8211; blue, indigo and violet &#8211; are more likely to be scattered away, while the lower end of the spectrum &#8211; red, orange and yellow &#8211; are less easily scattered.</p>
<p><div id="attachment_95697" style="width: 260px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/transit-setting-sun.jpg"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/transit-setting-sun-250x165.jpg" alt="Transit of Venus from Japan. 'Japanese fishermen before the 'Great Sun of Hiroshima'. Credit: Niki Gaida" width="250" height="165" class="size-thumbnail wp-image-95697" srcset="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/transit-setting-sun-250x165.jpg 250w, https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/transit-setting-sun-580x384.jpg 580w, https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/transit-setting-sun.jpg 633w" sizes="(max-width: 250px) 100vw, 250px"/></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Credit: Niki Gaida</p></div>When the Sun is close to the horizon, you’re seeing it distorted by more of the Earth’s atmosphere, scattering away the bluer photons and making it appear red. </p>
  
<div style=""><center>');
}
//--&gt;
</script></center></div> 
<p>When there’s smoke and pollution in the air, it enhances the effect and it will look even redder.</p>
<p>If the Sun is high in the sky, where it has the least amount of atmospheric interference, it will appear more blue. </p>
<p><div id="attachment_103795" style="width: 260px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sun-astrocolors.jpg"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sun-astrocolors-250x186.jpg" alt="The Sun, with AR1800 on July 28, 2013. This sunspot poses a slim threat for M-class flares the next few days, NASA says. Credit and copyright: César Cantú. " width="250" height="186" class="size-thumbnail wp-image-103795" srcset="https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sun-astrocolors-250x186.jpg 250w, https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sun-astrocolors-580x431.jpg 580w, https://web.archive.org/web/20160525215525im_/http://www.universetoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sun-astrocolors.jpg 799w" sizes="(max-width: 250px) 100vw, 250px"/></a><p class="wp-caption-text">The Sun. Credit and copyright: César Cantú.</p></div>We’re so familiar with the Sun being yellowish-orange, that astronomers will artificially change the color of their images to look more yellowy.</p>
<p>But really, the Sun looks like a pure white ball &#8211; especially when you’re out in space.</p>
<p>Interestingly, the color of the Sun is very important to astronomers. They use a technique called spectroscopy to stretch out the spectrum of light coming from a star. Dark lines in this spectrum tell you exactly what it’s made of. </p>
<p>You can see which stars have high amounts of metals, or which are mostly hydrogen and helium, leftover from the Big Bang.</p>
<p>This color also tells you the temperature of the star. Cooler stars are actually redder. Betelgeuse is only 3500 Kelvin. Hotter stars, like Rigel, can get above 10000 Kelvin, and they look blue.</p>
<p>Our own Sun has a temperature of almost 5800 Kelvin, and when viewed outside of our atmosphere, appears white. in colour.</p>
  
<div style=""><center>');
}
//--&gt;
</script>
</center></div> 
 
